				\begin{document}$$\text {CAN}$$\end{document} is to encode the task of function scope identification to a sequence of three action states NI (i.e., next inclusion), NE (i.e., next exclusion), and FE (i.e., function end). With the aforementioned assumption, the binaries of interest consist of several functions and the functions in a binary do not intermingle, that is, each function only contains its machine instructions, data, or jump-tables and do not contain any machine instruction of other functions. Each function can be therefore viewed as a collection of bytes where each byte is from a machine instruction of this function (i.e., instruction byte) or data/jump-tables inside this function (i.e., non-instruction byte). To clarify how to proceed over a binary function given a sequence of action states, let us imagine this binary program including many instruction and non-instruction bytes as a tape of many cells wherein each cell contains a instruction or non-instruction byte and a pointer firstly points to the first cell in the tape. The action state NI includes the current instruction or non-instruction byte in the current cell to the current function and moves the pointer to the next cell (i.e., the next instruction or non-instruction byte). The action state NE excludes the current instruction or non-instruction byte in the current cell from the current function and moves the pointer to the next cell. The action state FE counts the current instruction or non-instruction byte in the current cell, ends the current function, starts reading a new function, and moves the pointer to the next cell.

